text: I'm speculating here, but stay with me. We know Marvel Studios/Disney made a deal with Fox to use Quicksilver in Avengers: AoU, maybe the deal was temporary use. I mean we sort of saw a really young Scarlett Witch in X-men DoFP, but maybe that's the deal. Fox takes Quicksilver, Marvel Studios/Disney takes Scarlett Witch. We don't see Quicksilver in the final battle sequence of this trailer, so it has led me to believe that Quicksilver will probably die in Avengers AoU, in keeping with the contract with Fox who will use the character more in upcoming X-men films (particularly X-men Apocalypse). Meanwhile, Scarlett Witch will remain in the Marvel Cinematic Universe. The only real shred of evidence I have of this is the final battle sequence of this trailer. Quicksilver is no where to be seen nor any evidence of his powers at use. Then again, we don't see Vision either, who we know is in this film as well. So it goes something like this, (Potential Spoilers) Quicksilver and Scarlett Witch before they became "Miracles" were seen rioting over something. Baron von Strucker offers them powers to help save the world, but it doesn't go so well for the twins. The twins are empowered but possessed by Loki's Scepter (an Infinity stone, I might add) and used to do the work of von Strucker. At this point, Strucker either allows Ultron to take the twins or Ultron simply takes them, regardless Ultron has possession of them. Ultron and the Twins make a robot army (along with Vision at some point) to fight the Avengers. Chaos ensues, and amongst the chaos, Quicksilver is the first to snap out of his possession (maybe because of Vision). Scarlett witch is still a slave, and when Quicksilver sees her do bad things, he attempts to stop her but fails when someone kills Quicksilver (maybe Ultron). Scarlett Witch (much in the same way Hawkeye joins the Avengers in the first film) snaps out of her possession and fights with the Avengers. This is all speculation, so I guess we'll find out May 1st if this is true, but hey one can hope, because I'm still very intrigued!

text: For everyone asking about the video shaking: When you upload a video on YT and this video has a lot of movements, YT detects it and asks you if you want it to "stabilize" the video. The problem is that most of the time, the movements in the video are totally intentional, so the "stabilizing" just ruins everything (I had the case once). I may be wrong, but I think it's the problem, here (and probably someone already explained what I just said or gave the correct answer, in the comments...). The fact is you can undo this operation, so I wonder why it's still like this...

What happened to make you so complacent, uncharitable and reactionary? It's a movie trailer - why would you react as if it was a personal affront. This is a movie. It's entertainment, a cause for good will and enjoyment. We are all here for fun. Please keep negativity, bashing and petty brand-wars out of this. What in your entire life made you think that the world owed you perfection in every second? Save your outrage for the graver things in life. text: Over dramatized soundtrack, loud drums. Cheesy one liners Generic fade in and outs. Overused plot with slight variation. And people are still going to devour this by the millions.  The more movies I see coming out of Hollywood recently, the more I think I can do twice a better job at what's being released now. There are some gems here and there, but they're very rare, and really require a good script writer, actual story, and character development, without simplified or nonsensical dialogue, special effects, but an actual story progression with a prologue, conflict introduction, build up, battle, conflict resolve and an ending that makes sense. Of course you don't have to follow the usual formula, there's movies that were successful with a very unique and complex storyline such as Mr.Nobody. Overall I think this has boosted my confidence in what I am writing at the moment, and think it would definitely impress people now that I see the standard at which Hollywood is releasing short handed movies to the common movie enthusiast.

text: LOVE THIS TRAILER   First off, there are a couple things that i noticed watching it a couple times, that i thought i'd point out... maybe some you knew, maybe some you didn't and some things that just might not mean a lot... but be cool anyways. So.... potential spoilers??      1. At the very beginning, we see Ultron giving a bit of back story to the twins. A glance at Ultron sitting on the... throne? shows him wearing what looks like Scarlett Witch's red cloak/shawl, that she can be seen wearing later on in the trailer. Just before this we see a far pan of the entirebuilding, which i speculate to be some kind of Hydra base. Likely, the original and main base where Baron von Strucker operated from? In previous trailers, we'd seen a man working with operating equipment that was likely Baron himself. The throne would be barons, and this makes sense- since the twins were originally kept in Hydra custody, that is where they'd be most likely to appear first. It looks like they walked in on Ultron who was waiting for them... presumably with her cloak to get her attention? I dont know... shits cool though.  2.Very next thing is Ultron removing a sort of cable from the back of his head. now, this could mean absolutely nothing, and probably does... but as most obsessive comic book fans do, i will proceed to over-analyze everything. Could this present some sort of weakness to Ultron? Is it either him somehow upgrading himself, or is it possible he is in need of occaisional recharging? Who knows? But seeing as how Ultron is an incredibly durable villian whos outer shell is supposed to be nearly impenetrable... maybe this could bode well?  3. Cap tries to pull a car off the destroyed road by its bumper and people ultimately fall to their death. Things arent built the way they used to be  4. Tony offers his perspective on reasons to fight. This is definitely a different answer than what i know cap's would be, so we have more perspective as we get closer to Civil War.  5. Bruce and Natasha getting hot and heavy, this could be... interesting.  6. Watching everyone get suited up, right after Cap grabs his helmet... what looks to be a scene with Klaw priming a weapon of his... since we already know Andy Serkis is going to be playing Ulysses Klaw (Or at least its very obvious if you know how the character looks like), this claw-like weapon is definitely belonging to him. You can sort of make out his clothing which looks like what he wore in the other trailer, and the weapon aptly relates to his last name, while trading out the standard sonic cannon for what looks somewhat like pairs of tuning forks? That seems like a pretty cool spin on the weapon to give it more relevance.Â   7. Tony has Loki's scepter!!! Dont know why, but he thought about it enough to still wear the one arm of the suit incase touching it would hurt him somehow. I imagine it could help in the fight...  8. Cap doesn't have any plans tomorrow night. Dont know why that doesnt surprise me, but he doesnt seem like the clubbing type.  9. Update... Ultron is a taaaall muthafucka  10. Scarlett Witch Controls Scarlett Johansson... and her eyes turn a freaky red. So where we saw in a previous trailer, hulk having a case of pinkeye? Probably the same reason.Â   11. You can see the spit fly from cap's mouth as he gets rekt by Quickie(yes im calling him that, i dont like typing it all out every time) Â which actually made me laugh  12. Taunting doesnt work in Thor's favour.  13. From a birds eye view, when everyone is fighting the drones, we see S.W. also lending a hand... showcasing pretty cool powers and seeming to have switched sides. Quickie cant be found, but im sure he's around somewhere.  14. Hulk still lives by the same motto... "i'm always angry"  15. Finally, a look at GODDAMN VISION!!! And not looking corny at all either, wonderfully done ;)

text: @Marvel Entertainment This is bad ass. I don't know if that was a tease to Wolverine with claws or what , but it was a nice touch. I can wait to see how this catalogues within the rest of the MCU. This being the proverbial straw that broke the camel's back and which leads our favorite billionaire, playboy, philanthropist to become a reprimanding republican for superheroes . . .   I really favor what part Spider-Man will play in this afterwards. Though I am a bit unsure on just dropping him into the mix. Mostly because I don't know how he fits into the story at the moment. And, once he's implemented into the fold, how would his presence be explained?   An origin story is a bit like beating the dead horse, but, it gives purpose. A brief synopsis would do. I just find it hard to accept him because he's just being pasted within the universe with no rhyme or reason.  Unless it will be explained in Captain America : Civil War.   I feel Spidey would've been a nice addition to Netflix's The Defenders; working with Daredevil, Luke Cage, Jessica Jones, and Iron Fist. That way if it was more to explore, you can let that be the start. Well that just my opinion.   All and all, this was a great trailer,  and I hope to be blown away by this film.  #AvengersAssemble

text: THE RED SKULL FORESHADOWING? At the 1:42 mark, there is a second short clip of Scarlet Witch in front of an exploding building. Between her and the building out to the right is a campaign poster written in Cyrillic letters. (Anyone out there who can read Cyrillic letters, so we can get a translation?)Â  To throw an election poster up on a lamppost struck me as such a "strange" detail" to put into a superhero film, so I took a closer look The poster is held in "fascist" vibe, complete with a black uniform on the candidate, who looked a bit like Baron von Strucker (the Hydra villain you see at the end of Captain America 2) which didn't make any sense since I assume that you (even in Russia) can not buy a candidacy if you are a foreigner ... ;) But what if the candidate is a politician bought by (or even named) Alexander Lukin?... In the Captain America comics, stretching from the Winter Soldier story and far after the Civil War historyline is a plot involving a very important gentleman who was completely omitted in Winter Soldier movie; Alexander Lukin. A Russian billionaire, oil magnate and mega corporation owner (Kronas Industries) with great political power. He is also a man posessed by the red skull who used a Cosmic Cube (Tesseract) to move his consciousness into him. What if Hydra used Loki's spear (the mind gem) to locate the red skulls consciousness and place him within Lukins body?...Â  What if Ultrons doings is the MCU version of Stamford?Â  What if the MCU version of Senator Gordon Wright (Lukins/Red skull U.S. political puppet) isn't running for president (as in the Captain America comics), but instead advocating for whatever is going to pass for the Superhero Registration Act?Â  This would then have its dramatic and tragic culmination in Captain America, Civil War ...

text: Okay. I have officially had it with Marvel.  The 2012 Avengers film was great, at the time. I haven't watched it in a long time so I don't know how it holds up today. Iron Man 3 was a disappointment, especially coming out right after The Avengers and the fact I liked the first Iron Man film from 2008. Thor: The Dark World was an abortion of a two-hour digital intermediate. Awful pacing plus an awful sound mix. The Winter Soldier was the most "cold-in-the-brain" of the MCU, and I liked it better than the previous two. It hardly impressed me, however. Guardians of the Galaxy was a fun time, best MCU since The Avengers, but I realized all the jarring tonal shifts in the film when thinking back to it. Big Hero 6 (non-MCU) was cute, but I felt it was watered-down and reliant on too many cliches.  Judging from this trailer alone, Age of Ultron looks like a bloated mess of artifice. Nothing in the trailer was appealing to me compared to the earlier "Pinocchio" teaser. Buildings collapse, citizens fleeing, bad guy says something bad in a deep LFE-shaking voice. The shot at 1:08 sold me on this film being a "No." Too much loud, dramatic music, Inception horns, expensive but ugly CGI. I could be wrong, but I have a strong feeling this is going to be a mess, and God-willing, it will be the end of Marvel once the reviews come in.

text: Someone said here that it's boring that Marvel's making movies about unheard heroes. Okay, first of all, if you're talking about GOTG and Ant Man, and you don't know who they are - you don't have to be a fan of them - then you're not really that much of a comic fan to begin with. But that's what makes Marvel movies great. They can take characters who are unpopular outside of the fan base and make it amazing for the layperson, for the person who isn't obsessed as a lot of us are about the genre, myself included. DC certainly cannot say the same. I don't think they have much confidence in any of their characters beyond Superman and Batman because they seem to be constantly rehashing them (especially Superman).Â   Another thing is that DC has jumped on the Superhero Team movie thing a little over a decade too late to ever catch up with what Marvel's doing. They've spent precious time on substandard movies like Green Lantern, which could have been amazing had it been done right, while Marvel was building a cohesive universe, writing and planning for years, culminating in some of the best superhero works ever, both in movies and in TV land. DC in the scheme of things has only just begun to get their shit together for standalone movies leading up to the elusive Justice League movie. I like DC, too, They're great where animated series are concerned but not so hot in the movie sector. I do like a few of their movies, too, but DC has a long way to go to touch Marvel with a hundred foot pole where the comic book movie genre is concerned. At least Marvel has faith in their abilities to breathe life into their lesser known characters and make it amazing for fans and laypeople alike.Â

text: Ending scene for this movie: The Avengers lie scattered & defeated. Ultron hovers triumphantly over the debris of the battle and proclaims, "ARE THERE NO MORE HEROES!?" After a few seconds of daunting silence a slow rumble starts all around which steadily increases to a violent quake. The damaged buildings around Ultron starts to break apart violently, hurling large pieces of steel and concrete towards him. Ultron takes several heavy blows, falls to the ground as the debris continue to rain down on him as he is buried by several fallen buildings. A battered and broken Ultron slowly crawls out only to be hit by multiple high impact darts which simultaneously electrify and after several moments of excruciating "pain" Ultron is down and out. A lone individual walks up to Ultron with hands extending towards him then stops. The slow rumbling resumes this time focusing on Ultron's body. There is shaking all around as the individual's hands slowly move apart from each other and then in one quick movement (then in slow mo) Ultron's body is ripped apart into several pieces. The individual turns and looks up (facing the camera now) "Target down Sir!" - Skye/Daisey/Quake. Coulson and Agent May are hovering above in the "Bus" The rest of the AoS team are on the ground holding their rifles with smoking barrels. The Avengers come to and look around then up at the "Bus". Coulson says over the PA system, "Shawarma anyone?"

In Cap 2 you guys do realize she only kissed Cap to maintain cover right?  Their relationship is more big bro little sis. text: Okay, let's see possibilities on who dies. Note that I may possibly not know info that changes my theories.  Tony Stark, Captain America and Thor all will not die because they are set to be in future movies (Cap 3 and Thor 3)  It is possible that Hawkeye or Black Widow die, but we see them in the last fight, maybe they die In the very end  Scarlet Witch and Quicksilver are possibilities but then again, we see Scarlet Witch in the last fight, but we don't see Quicksilver... Possibly he is moving so fast, or he isn't present, or he is dead... But the actor for Quicksilver's contract still has more movies to do.  The Hulk might die, but really? The Hulk?  The Vision might die to save the team. But that's a dumb move, introduce a new character and kill him off Immediately? No.  Ultron dying? maybe...  Nick Fury is a possibility, hmmm...  That girl Agent, maybe...  Haters, likely...  And I really don't see other characters guaranteed to be in the movie to die.  So peace out, and theorize, be sure to say any possibilities I might've missed.  -Final Ninja Zero

text: Ultron = Ultron + Dr Doom + Magneto? To me it seems as if Ultron in the MCU combines trades of three characters: 1. Ultron (obviously), 2. Dr Doom (in the trailer we see Ultron on a throne (wearing a cape?) in a fortress/castle in a fictional eastern european countryÂ Sokovia) You just have to change Sokovia to Latveria to get a pretty good version of Doom. Doom has his Doombots, Ultron has his Army of Ultrons. Ultron even has blasts similar to Dr Doom 3. Magneto (In the comics Scarlet Whitch and Quicksilver were part of the brotherhood of evil mutans lead by magneto, after a few issues they changed teams and became part of the Avengers. Thats exactly what seems to happen in the movie. But in this case its Ultron, not Magneto manipulating them  To me it seems that because Marvel doesn't own the rights to Fantastic Four And The X Men, they try to integrate some trades into characters they own. In the trailer you see Hawkeyes new arrows that look A LOT like Wolverines claws. I think its quite possible that Hawkeys will take the role that Wolverine has in the comics. He is a grumpy killer who seems to be a bit of a loner.  Please tell me what you think about my theory, guys

text: Now this is just a theory: Ultron was a dormant peacekeeping program. suggesting he was created X amount of years ago (but without sentience) by someone but never used to an extent. Ultron says that he was designed to save the world. Now that could've been his main function when he was designed years ago. His main function in this film is to protect the world so that the Avengers don't have to. That is Starks plan for Ultron. So Stark finds the old program and figures hey this will work. So the question is: who made the program all those years ago. So the big part of this theory is that Hank is the first person to design Ultron. Now im 100% cool if they want to leave it ambiguous and its all Tony's doing but this is for the ones bitching about it not being Pym's creation and want that bit of hope. So a while back there was the first official clip of Antman at SDCC. In the clip Hank comment that superheroes are a "goddamn joke". This obviously indicates he has no respect or love for heroes in the present. So his idea back then was to create something that ultimately protects the world without the use of heroes. He probably saw himself becoming one in the future and didnâ€™t want that <still working on that part. He wanted Ultron to protect the world but something got in the way. Be it personal/moral issues or the government that stopped him. Howard â€˜stark is in Antman so maybe thereâ€™s more of a connection. Maybe Howard stole or just vaulted it and thats how Tony gets it. So the program is halted and awaiting to be rebooted in the future by Tony where he makes the mistake of giving it free rein on the worlds info and takes its programing tooooo seriously. So theres my â€œHank is still the creator of Ultronâ€ theory. Now Ant man is only 3 months after AoU so I see there being references here in there for a movie that should still be fresh in minds.Â

text: LIKE THIS COMMENT SO PEOPLE SEE IT AND FINALLY UNDERSTAND WHATS GOING ON! (Not fishing for likes, just trying to help people).  Can't believe there's still people who think the MCU (Marvel Cinematic Universe) is part of the Xmen films. MCU is Disney, Xmen is Fox. I don't understand how people could possibly think they're part of the same world. You wouldn't watch Harry Potter and then say it's part of Lord of the Rings. Just because they're the same genre doesn't make them part of the same universe lol. Until now, the Amazing Spider-Man was stand alone by Sony but now they're revamping him and introducing him into the Avengers world. Don't tell me you thought the Amazing Spider-Man was part of the same story too?   It doesn't take a genius to realise that they're not intertwining with each other. If people actually realised this and watched the films in order then the world would be a less stressful place.   AVENGERS films- Ironman The Incredible Hulk Ironman 2 Thor Captain America: the First Avenger The Avengers Ironman 3 Thor: the Dark World Captain America: the Winter Soldier  Guardians of the Galaxy Avengers: Age of Ultron Ant-Man Captain America: Civil War Doctor Strange Guardians of the Galaxy 2 Spider-Man revamp  Thor: Ragnarok Avengers: Infinity War part 1 Black Panther Captain Marvel Avengers: Infinity War part 2 Inhumans  X-MEN films- X-Men X-2 X-Men 3: the Last Stand X-Men Origins: Wolverine X-Men: First Class The Wolverine  X-Men: Days of Future Past X-Men: Apocalypse Wolverine 3 X-Force   As for the Amazing Spider-Man films, eradicate them from your memory, they're over. The new version of the character is set to star in Captain America: Civil War. Okay is everyone clear now? X-Men and the Avengers films are DIFFERENT! If you took the time to watch ALL the films rather than watching the odd one that appeals to you things may make a little more sense. They're like big comic books, you wouldn't read at random parts, it requires you to read from beginning to end. Also, for those who think that was somehow Wolverine in the trailer now know that it wasn't! (It was Hawkeye loading his quickfire arrows). The only way anyone can carry on being confused is if they don't read this comment! DO YOURSELF A FAVOUR!

text: I really loved this trailer so many cool shots especially the scene where hulk iron man, captain america, hawkeye blackwidow and thor are leaping into the scene in the snow that was truly epic!!!that will now be my screen saver lol.   I also liked how they used shots to resemble scenes from the comics now I'm not really a big comic reader but I do know my fair bit and I know the  Second shot of ultron sat in his throne with a hood over him is a reference crimson cowl who was ultron in disguise I think who also assembled the masters of evil so maybe we might see a glimpse or something of them.   I liked how they are also setting up for Captain America civil war as well plus I liked how we got a bit of comedy in this trailer but it was still dark in its own way.  I do think marvel are doing great with not spoiling things in there trailers like sony did with the Amazing Spiderman 2 now I have to be honest I loved the amazing spider man 2 it did have it's pros and cons like most films do. Also some people are a bit stunned about the romance between hulk and black widow and that it should of been between her and hawkeye or steve rogers. Now 1. Hawkeye and widow were close friends and I think hawkeye saved her so the only chemistry really between them is good friendship. 2. In the winter soldier widow had to kiss steve Rogers so they couldn't get caught by hydra plus she was trying to set him up with a girl, so I do like what Joss Weedon has done here.  Lastly if you pause at 1 minute and 48 seconds when ultron is in the sky and you see his army of drones if you look closely on the left hand corner there appears to be someone standing on some rubble dressed in black and I think someone is standing next to it, now it could be a statue but I would like to know what other people think it could be that's if you spot it.  That's all I got to say about this trailer is that it is absolutely magnificent bring on April 23rd because I live in the UK

text: The Avengers is one of, if not the most overrated, lackluster,Â contentless and uninspiring pieces of rotten vomit that was ever put on the screen. And I have such point of view on this movie-catastrophe not simply because of its popularity and current rentability. That's because this piece of vomit does not deserveÂ anything from what was attributed to it. Poorly scripted and realized plot, which gives no investigation to the actual story. Poorly made and represented characters. Captain America is the most uninteresting and uninspiringÂ character in a whole film, even considering the fact that he is supposed to be a leader and the core of the group, but it does not say muchÂ since every character in that film was blend and uninspiring. Overuse and formulaic humor, that most of the time feels out of the place. Caricaturistic, not interesting villain, that only able to threat your sister's wet pants. List goes on and on. And there is no excuse for this bullcrap, such as ''That movie was meant to be fun'', ''It's not supposed to be taken seriously''. Well, I'm taking seriously the fact that most people overacting and overpraising dull and uninspiring shit product that this movie was. What, you want to talk about the differences between everybody's taste and opinion and that you have to respect them? Well, most of those bandwagon passengers, who like to make such banal argument, forget about it completely when they take shit at someone like twilight fans, while I find it hilarious, because I don't see a big difference between both. This doesn't giveÂ any hope for its to at least be different, interesting and creative. The only difference is, the trailer tries make this movie look like the emo version of the same bullcrap that has been done by these hacksÂ three years ago. I take Sam Raimi's Spider-Man 2 over every shitfest that this company had put any day.

text: Avengers is one of, if not the most overrated, lackluster, contentless and uninspiring piece of a rotten vomit that was ever put on the screen. And I have such point of view on this movie catastrophe not simply because of its popularity and current rentability. That's because this piece of vomit does not deserve anything from what was attributed to it. Poorly scripted and realized plot, which gives no investigation to the actual story. Poorly made and represented characters. Captain America is the most uninteresting and uninspiring character in a whole film, even considering the fact, that he is supposed to be a leader and the core of the group, but it does not say much since every character in that film was blend and uninspiring. Overuse and formulaic blend humor, that most of the times feels out of the place. Caricaturistic, not interesting villain, that only able to treat your sisters wet pants. List goes on and on. And there is no excuse for this bullcrap, such as ''That movie was meant to be fun'', ''It's not supposed to be taken seriously''. Well, I'm taking seriously the fact, that most people overacting and overpraising dull and uninspiring shit product that that movie was. What, you want to talk about the differences between everybody's taste and opinion, and that you have to respect them? Well, most of those bandwagon passengers who likes to make such banal argument, forget about it completely, when they take shit at someone like twilight fans, while, I find it hilarious, because, I don't see a big difference between both. This doesn't give any hope for it to at least be different, interesting and creative. The only difference is, the trailer try make this movie look like the emo version of the same bullcrap that has been done by these hacks three years ago. I take Sam Raimi's Spider-Man 2 over every shit-fest that this company has put any day. Â Â   Kappa.

text: So, how I think a plot is gonna go: Thor dies (somehow), and then he appears in the cave in Valhalla (the one we saw in one of those trailers). Cap takes his hammer and wields Thor's power (briefly), otherwise that scene with Avengers trying to lift Thor's hammer is pretty pointless. At the end Cap and iron man part ways to create their own teams of Avengers (Civil War) Some of you might say: "Hey, dumbass, there's a third movie with Thor, Ragnarok, how can he be dead? Well, remember, that during the Civil War in comics Tony creates a cybernetic clone of Thor and names it Ragnarok. So, since already have a Civil War movie, we can assume that the third movie about Thor is gonna be about his clone, not about an event. Or at least that's what I think.

text: This looks.. interesting.. from what I'm reading and seeing, it almost seems like they're trying to cramp in Too much into this one movie. I know it's a trend marvel have started lately, with Captain America 2 and mostly Guardians of the galaxy, with their strong desire to bring in as many characters from the marvel universe as possible.. but I don't agree that that is the best course to take to be honest.. It leaves smoother, cleaner and more polished movies if they take it at a slower pace in my opinion. But then again, marvel have presented some pretty impressive movies in the past, and if there's a reason any of marvels latest movies have felt a bit rushed, un-polished or "meh", it's because they've worked on THIS movie.. So I still have my hopes up for this one.. but if this one isn't as impressive as i'm hoping for it to be.. my opinion about marvels upcoming movies might start to change.. Â Â

text: I have the perfect idea for an end credit scene for this movie, okay so as we've seen from a clip already Bruce Banner is feeling tremendous guilt for the lives lost over the hulks rage.  There's been rumors swirling of hulk being sent into space by the avengers because he's too uncontrollable. However I think banner himself blasts him self off in a rocket as a self-sacrifice and this leads me to my 2 alternate endings.   Okay so my first would be we his capsule flying through space and then it cuts to starlets with his feet up in The Milano listening to his 2nd mixtape when the capsule skims past the ship barely missing it and a surprised quill looks out the window and goes like "what the hell?!" And we see a kind of mini kid like groot peeping out the window barely the height of the window and says "I am groot!" This could then lead onto hulk joining the guardians in their sequel.  My 2nd idea is something if not to happen in this film then the guardians sequel if my first idea happened. So hulk crashes on some asteroid and a dazed hulk stumbles out of the capsule and we see an intimidating shadow leaning over him who is none other than thanos who looks just as physical as the hulk side by side. In his hand he should have the soul gem or perhaps Bruce could have took the soul gem with him and thanos is here to intercept it. He takes the gem and smiles and the scene cuts.  Now saying as loads of people want a world war hulk movie this is  the perfect way to do it. For infinity war part 1 what better an idea for a mind controlled hulk to be the villain and completely destroys earth which is all a distraction for thanos to collect any remaining stones on earth this could also easily allow an avengers and guardians crossover.

text: The way Spader says "I'll take that from them first," is my favorite line, anyone who hasn't seen him as Raymond Reddington in The Blacklist should check out some video or episodes, his little short stories from every corner of the world are the best part. He's beyond perfect for a role like this, his voice just sounds naturally evil, but he's usually the bad guy you end up rooting for, Ultron isn't quite so easy to understand. He doesn't do it because of some horrible past like say Magneto, he just thinks humans should be eradicated, but for him to be really successful as a bad guy I hope they find a way to make him relatable, because the best villains are the ones you don't want to die.

text: Thor challenges others to lift the hammer, none can do it apart from Cap managed to shift it very slightly which he doesn't notice and Black Widow declines to try. Vision lifts the hammer later on. We see Black Widow's back-story more, she was from some assassin school or something and apparently she was sterilized. There was a lot of Black Widow/Hulk romance stuff which came out of nowhere a little but it worked pretty well. Hawkeye has a wife and kids which he was keeping secret. Ultron is an alright villain but was lacking in character beyond generic Whedon quipping. At the end Cap assembles a bunch of new members for the Avengers including Scarlet Witch, Falcon, War Machine and one more if I'm remembering correctly. Quicksilver dies saving Hawkeye. It ends setting up Thor seeking Ragnorok and Cap doubting Stark's ability to resist tampering futher with the world, and Hulk goes AWOL on his own. Post-credits scene shows Thanos putting on the gauntlet and saying 'I'll have to do it myself' or something. No second post-credits scene. It was shit lol.

text: Incredible movie, not the best I've seen, but definitely one of the best Marvel movies. Great action, good character development, witty and catchy dialogue, a menacing and formidable villain (Ultron) who has all the means of breaking the Avengers.Â   The addition of Scarlet Witch and Quicksilver was a good move, they have their moments and you get a sense of feeling towards them.  All in all, great movie. Now I feel empty inside, been waiting three years building up for this movie and now it's done.Â   Now I have to wait three more years for Infinity War. At least we'll be getting some great movies along the way: Civil War, Thor: Ragnorak (hyped about this one), Doctor Strange, Guardians of the Galaxy 2 (loved the first one).  My current favorite Marvel movies atm:  1. Age of Ultron 2. Guardians of the Galaxy 3. The Avengers 4. Winter Soldier 5. Thor: The Dark World  Cheers!

text: A summary of the movie if anyone is too impatient:  -The twins join the Avengers. (obvious) -Quicksilver dies in a heroic scene saving Hawkeye - who's protecting a child. -Vision lifts Thors hammer. (A few people started clapping, like da fuq?) -The Avenger roster in the end has changed, and includes: Scarlet Witch, Black Widow, Captain America, Falcon, War Machine, Vision.Â  -Vision kills the last Ultron bot. -Hulk disappears by the end of the movie. -Thor goes back to Asguard. -ULTRON is a bad ass, but literally only killed one person from what I remember.Â  -Mid-credit scene is Thanos getting the Infinity Gauntlet and saying "I guess I'll have to do it my self"Â  -There is a new Avengers tower/building @ the end of the movie -The Infinity Gem in Loki's sceptre is a yellow gem, that goes into the Visions forehead (I think it's the soul gem?) -There is no post-credit scene, but there is writing stating: "The Avengers will return"'

text: MAJOR SPOILER ALERT! - The Stone of Mind was previously concealed on Loki's Sceptre, given to the adopted Asgardian by The Other. Given the Other's boss is Thanos, presumably it was the only Stone held by the Titan. It allowed Loki to hypnotize everyone touched by the sceptre, although it only works in contact with skin; once Loki attempt to mind control Iron Man but hit the Arc Reactor on his chest, the magic was unsuccessful. Given its energy signature is similar to the Tesseract's, the Sceptre was neccessary to bypass a failsafe built by Erik Selvig on the Tesseract-harnessing machine that created a wormhole above New York.[9] After Loki was defeated, Hydra took the sceptre from Stark Tower (presumably through undercover S.H.I.E.L.D. agents who helped Tony Stark clean the place) and researched on it. On Baron Strucker's hidden facility at Sokovia, various test subjects were exposed to the Sceptre, with only a set of twins surviving and consequently developing superpowers: Pietro Maximoff, who became a speedster, and Wanda Maximoff, who developed telekinesis and mental manipulation.[11] Once Tony Stark discovered the roundabouts of the Sceptre, the Avengers reassembled to recover it in Sokovia. During the three days prior to Thor's return to Asgard, Tony discovered the stone held information inside it akin to computer language. Tony decided that the data was just what he needed to develop an artificial intelligence that would evolve on J.A.R.V.I.S., Ultron. With the help of Bruce Banner and J.A.R.V.I.S., Ultron managed to be put into operation, but suddenly decided he would not try save humankind as planned, and begun a plan to exterminate humans. Using one Iron Legion robot to stow away the Sceptre, Ultron took over the former Hydra base and remained the research on the Sceptre. Ultron ultimately decided to create an artificial lifeform that would be better than humans, using vibranium taken from Ulysses Klaue, Helen Cho's biotechnology cradle, and the Infinity Stone which Ultron broke out of the sceptre. While Ultron assembled the creature, Thor discovered in a vision that the gem was an Infinity Stone. While attempting to destroy the android which the Avengers had hijacked and brought to Stark Tower, Thor wound up awakening Vision, who upon emergency turned out to be not as ill-intentioned as Ultron. After Ultron was defeated, Thor had no problem with leaving Vision with the Stone inside him, considering it in good hands. However, Thor was certain another of the stones had appeared because an upper force was using its powers to discover the gems' wereabouts. This turned out to be Thanos, who got the Infinity Gauntlet from the Asgardian armory and decided to continue the Stone-recovering mission by himself.[12]

text: Don't watch this movie if you've ever been to a physics class, ever. Because it involves a cunning plan of lifting an f-ing city into the air to throw it down again, causing an "extinction event". You know that raising the thing in the air takes just as much energy as it will produce falling down, right? And no-one even bothers to explain how Ultron manages to lift a city miles into the air, as if that's trivially obvious - the trick is to throw it down again, you see! No-one's ever thought of THAT before!

text: Just saw it. It is every bit as good as it looks. It brings new characters, more characterization to existing characters, the epic battle sequences we've come to expect, and on-point acting. To be honest though, it really doesn't do anything new. Bad guy emerges, good guys get hit hard by initial contact, get stronger, and then have a massive battle with bad guy, good guys miraculously emerge victorious. It's great fun to see, and the whole thing has been polished to a mirror shine, but if you're looking for an interesting plot, this isn't the place to look for it.

text: What's unusual is that ultron's line of "I was designed to be pure, to be beautiful...people would have looked to the skies and seen hope...I'll take that from them first" calls to mind two specific lines from Mary shelley's "Frankenstien", specifically "I ought to be thy Adam, but I am rather the fallen angel..." and the line "if I cannot inspire love, then I shall inspire fear". Additionally, Ultron's "Vision" ends up being jump-started awake by Thor's Lightning, adding even more of a frankenstien esque vibe to it allâ€”the difference being that vision is Ultron but without the egomaniacal, arrogant, and genocidal tendencies Ultron possessed. Finally, much as frankenstien's monster was assembled from various sources, so too was vision: Natasha retrieved him, helen cho fused the vibranium with artificial cells, Ultron had the idea, Steve distracted Ultron so Nat could get the cradle, Clint flew the cradle from Seoul to New York, Thor's Lightning awoke vision, vision is powered by the possibly sentient mind stone,  his voice and most of his base personality came from Tony through Jarvis, and Bruce helped Tony reconfigure Jarvis' matrix

text: I was hoping for a lot darker in AoU. Like *spoilers* â€¢Quicksilver's death: I know his sacrifice was sad, but he could have probably escaped the bullets, he should have died in a way where even as fast as he is, he couldn't escape it. â€¢The Citizens: Cap tries to save the people in the car, but it falls off the bridge. Then Thor saves them and we have a funny moment, but I think the people in it should have died, so we see that the people really do suffer from their mistakes (with their lives). â€¢Ultron: In that scene where he says "What doesn't kill you makes you stronger", we need more of that darker stuff, to make the movie more serious, I feel like Ultron was wasted a bit here. Most of it is just nitpicking but I was hoping for a darker movie than the first.

text: This movie was just SO GOOD. SO AWESOME. I don't understand all that hate. Plenty of character development for everyone, fantastic action (I've watched pretty much all of the superhero flicks and there is just no competition), interesting and complex plot, lots of themes and sub-themes, Ultron is a VERY deep and complex villain (honestly didn't expect that from a Marvel Movie) and team actually interacts with each other and... just have fun, doing it. They all like each other, unlike the first movie. Pretty much all of the jokes hit bullseye. It's not Stark's movie. It's everyone's. I don't think anyone ever managed to make a team movie such as good as this. Certainly not in superhero genre. It improves EVERYTHING from the first movie and ups everything to the next level. Marvel's second best movie after Winter Soldier.

Overall, I think it was one of the best Marvel movies made so far, with Guardians of The Galaxy, Winter Soldier, and Iron man 3 up there. author: edgar galarza

text: First off, I really liked this movie, like a lot. That doesn't mean I don't have my problems with it. I was expecting it to let's say "Grow up", now I didn't want this movie to have each character a dull forgettable adaptation of a beloved hero cough* Man of Steel cough* I just though they could ease up on the humor. Having it here or there (I mean you can't have Tony Stark, and not have him be a smart ass). The part when they where all trying to pick up Thor's Hammer is excellent my favorite part in the MUC thus far. And I don't know what people's hang up about Ultron having a sense of humor. He was made by Tony Stark. He is going to have a form humor in him, he gave Jarvis some. And he still have his sinister moments. His first encounter with The Avengers still gives is giving me chills just typing this, and when he crushes his own head. That was badass. For me it's number 7 on my MCU rank list.
author: Quint Dunaway

text: Walking out of the cinema, I loved this film. It was pure Marvel action, some scenes felt like they were ripped from comic pages at it was great. Although I was pretty underwhelmed in some points. The way the film was marketed was completely different to the actual film: way too many jokes when there didn't need to be ( I like humor in Marvel films but this was just overboard), Ultron was way less menacing than he was shown in the trailers, and while I get why he was childish at the start since he was pretty much a baby if you think about it, It still was a massive shit on the Ultron character. The pacing was very weird, now I only saw it once because I really only see films once, so maybe the second viewing will change my opinion on that. Overall, I really enjoyed it and it's really entertaining.

author: Noob noob

text: So many things went wrong with this movie. They should've grown a pair of balls this time and stuck to the dark tone that the trailers implied. In order to make Ultron feel menacing they also needed to make sure that he kills at least one character from the previous movies or maybe he manages to kill off a group of civilians. Anything to make it feel like he was actually more powerful to the Avengers. As it stands Iron Man alone kicked his ass without so much as breaking a sweat. The action scenes were also a huge letdown. Aside from Hulk vs Hulkbuster which was really cool the rest just lacked the memorable moments that the first movie did like Iron Man flying towards the wormhole blowing shit up, Hulk smashing Loki around, Hawkeye firing that arrow at Loki that blew up in his face or Captain America convincing the police officer to help him. Absolutely none of that in this movie they just throw punches and jump around a lot and the pacing was too sporadic. Actions scenes start every 15 minutes and then they end within another 5. The climax in particular was just a boring retread of the climax from the first movie but lacking the excitement that made that awesome. Didn't hate the movie because I still enjoy the characters and their chemistry but it was seriously disappointing and I think it might be a good thing that the Russo brothers are handling the next movies for now so we might actually get a darker movie where the Avengers get their asses kicked. Anyway sorry for the long post needed to vent my frustration :P

text: 5 reasons why Avengers Age of Ultron is the best Superhero movie   5.The Music: The soundtrack is absolutely fantastic. I could listen to it for 10 hours and never get tired. It's basically the first movie's theme with a pinch of excitement. Danny Elfman is of course one of my all time favorite music composers.  4. The Set Ups for future films: People are complaining that this is the problem Iron Man 2 had. It's nothing like that. The set ups are done very well. The set up for Thor Ragnarok was my favorite becuse it made me curious about what we're gonna get in that film. It didn't focus TOO much on the set ups like Iron Man 2 did though which is good.  3.The Humor: This the most common complant I'm hearing from people. There saying "But the trailers set up for a dark movie! Where did all this comedy come from?" Guys, it's an Avengers movie! It has to be fun! It has to be a film you can have a good time with. It's not a dark, boring DC movie. I laughed quite alot during this film. It was able to balance the humor with the drama perfectly too.  2. The Action: This movie had insane crazy action! The fight scene between Hulk and Iron Man was incredible! And that fight between Captain America and Ultron on the tuck was amazing. Also that final battle on the floating land was mind blowing. I had tears of joy leaking out of my eyes during it. The slow motion, the effects. Oh my god! Brilliant!  1. The Characters: The main reason I adore this movie is becuase of the characters. We got more back story for Hawkeye and Black Widow. And the Vision was handled in the best way possible. Tony Stark and Steve Rogers were setting up for Civil War very perfectly. And that scene were Scarlet Witch walked through the door in slo mo was epic. I was shocked when Quicksilver died. He wasn't a great character but he was still a decent incarnation. And Ultron: Everybody has ranted for no reason that Uktron was a weak villian and not threatning at all. Look, Ultron had the scense of humor so the audience can relate to him and make him more likable. Plus he had lots of serious moments out there. I wish War Machine and Falcon had more screen time though.

text: I got a better desired perspective from this trailer than I did from the movie itself.   - Beginning of the movie gave a tone that Ultron started off a good hero, after learning too much, Ultron becomes dark.  - Ultron didn't exactly come off as a great fear worthy of causing great panic to the public, this is mainly because they hardly involved him with humans on a world wide level   - Quicksilver died and he wasn't even properly developed enough for us to connect with him on an emotional level    - Ultron wasn't really even close to living up to his true potential at all given the strategy and knowledge of the entire internet, he had an ego yes but we are talking knowledge on an absolutely unbelievable scale   - Ultron didn't come off as a threat considering his robots are stick figures, he couldn't initiate his plan without the help of Quick silver and Scarlett witch, the final battle was featured in the trailer and just from looking at that part of the scene, Ultron lost.
